00:07:34.353 --> 00:07:38.090
My next book actually is
about apps and design

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:40.693
and I was really
interested in the tension

00:07:40.693 --> 00:07:41.827
between those instruments,

00:07:41.827 --> 00:07:43.896
which are incredibly
beautiful instruments.

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:45.831
The cello has been around
for several hundred years,

00:07:45.831 --> 00:07:48.067
the violin also has
a long history.

00:07:48.067 --> 00:07:51.003
How do we figure on
the role of apps and design

00:07:51.003 --> 00:07:53.505
in a modern sensibility
with a composer

00:07:53.505 --> 00:07:55.841
who is very intrigued by data?

00:07:55.841 --> 00:07:58.710
So, I came up with an iPad app

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:01.213
and what we are
going to be doing now is

00:08:01.213 --> 00:08:03.249
essentially
as a virtual string quartet

00:08:03.249 --> 00:08:05.150
with two turntables,
violin and cello.

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:07.319
So when I was
in the Arctic Circle

00:08:07.319 --> 00:08:08.720
with the Sierra Club crew,

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.223
we ended up meeting
this incredible tribe

00:08:11.223 --> 00:08:12.558
called the Gwich'in people

00:08:12.558 --> 00:08:14.694
and they are
one of the oldest nations...

00:08:14.727 --> 00:08:16.796
first nations
in North America.

00:08:16.796 --> 00:08:19.398
They are over
20,000 years old civilization.

00:08:19.398 --> 00:08:22.568
And I took a long walk with
one of their tribal elders

00:08:22.568 --> 00:08:24.737
and they would just look...
pointing at the landscape,

00:08:24.737 --> 00:08:26.205
I said,
"this is quite beautiful,

00:08:26.205 --> 00:08:28.741
it's really amazing,"
and the guy was essentially

00:08:28.741 --> 00:08:30.810
like "well, we don't know
how to describe this,

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:32.144
it shouldn't be green,"
you know.

00:08:32.144 --> 00:08:33.579
I was like, "Oh!" you know.

00:08:33.579 --> 00:08:36.915
So for me as a Southerner,
you know someone from DC,

00:08:36.915 --> 00:08:38.417
going to one
of the most remote

00:08:38.417 --> 00:08:40.586
northern parts of the U.S.
and seeing green,

00:08:40.586 --> 00:08:41.853
I thought that was amazing.

00:08:41.853 --> 00:08:44.123
For them,
it was a sign of disaster.

00:08:44.123 --> 00:08:47.893
So this next piece is
dedicated to the people that

00:08:47.893 --> 00:08:50.529
think that there's no
debate about climate change.

00:08:50.529 --> 00:08:52.531
So, this next piece
is called...

00:08:52.531 --> 00:08:53.866
"Check Your Math."

